WEBVTT

00:22.857 --> 00:25.025
♪ ♪

00:39.081 --> 00:40.875
(crowd cheering)

00:40.958 --> 00:43.043
MALE ANNOUNCER:
The rain has stopped.

00:43.127 --> 00:44.670
The excitement has really grown

00:44.754 --> 00:48.215
among this 40,000-strong
Wembley crowd.

00:48.299 --> 00:50.468
Safe to say that
every single one of them

00:50.551 --> 00:52.094
is on Henry Cooper’s side.

00:52.178 --> 00:53.679
(punches landing)

00:53.763 --> 00:55.681
MALE ANNOUNCER 2: And Cooper’s
eye is opening wider.

00:55.765 --> 00:57.558
It’s a shocking cut
above his left eye.

00:57.641 --> 01:00.478
He knows he’s got to get this
fight over with fairly quickly.

01:00.561 --> 01:02.146
Clay doesn’t like it.

01:02.229 --> 01:04.482
He pushes the referee, but the
referee’s having none of it.

01:04.565 --> 01:06.484
-Clay is mocking Cooper.
-CASSIUS: I’m over here.

01:06.567 --> 01:08.402
ANNOUNCER 2: Cooper knows.
He’s trying to get that left...

01:08.486 --> 01:09.945
-CASSIUS: I’m over here.
-...left hook now.

01:10.029 --> 01:11.322
-(bell dinging)
-Left hook. Oh, there he goes!

01:11.405 --> 01:12.990
-He just misses Clay.
-(crowd jeering)

01:13.073 --> 01:15.034
And he raises his hands
as he goes back to his corner,

01:15.117 --> 01:16.994
the crowd jeering him
all the way.

01:17.077 --> 01:19.330
My goodness, Cooper.

01:19.413 --> 01:21.457
ANGELO:
Is this a joke to you, kid?

01:21.540 --> 01:23.167
-What’d I do?
-Nothing.

01:23.250 --> 01:25.085
That’s the problem.
We had a fight plan.

01:25.169 --> 01:27.087
Plan? Angie, look at him.

01:27.171 --> 01:29.256
I’m beating the shit
out of that tomato can.

01:29.340 --> 01:30.841
Damn right he is.
Rumble, young man, rumble!

01:30.925 --> 01:32.134
-Ah!
-Ah!

01:32.218 --> 01:33.552
Listen, if you’re not
gonna keep your hands up,

01:33.636 --> 01:34.720
can you at least
finish him off?

01:34.804 --> 01:36.055
I don’t want to get
too close to him.

01:36.138 --> 01:37.807
I get any more of his blood
on my trunks,

01:37.890 --> 01:39.433
my mama ain’t never
gonna be able to get it out.

01:39.517 --> 01:42.186
Nobody gives a damn about
blood on some boxing trunks.

01:42.269 --> 01:43.687
These is my lucky trunks.

01:43.771 --> 01:44.772
Your mama’s still doing
your laundry?

01:44.855 --> 01:46.190
-(laughter)
-Shut up.

01:46.273 --> 01:47.733
Would you both
shut the fuck up?

01:47.817 --> 01:48.818
Here.

01:48.901 --> 01:50.444
Three rounds in,
and it’s not looking good

01:50.528 --> 01:52.613
-for Henry the Hammer.
-No, it is not.

01:52.696 --> 01:53.864
ANNOUNCER 2: This Wembley Park
crowd was expecting

01:53.948 --> 01:55.533
a better showing
from local lad Cooper

01:55.616 --> 01:57.493
against American upstart
Cassius Clay.

01:57.576 --> 01:59.954
They’ve been saying
the Louisville Lip’s theatrics

02:00.037 --> 02:02.081
overshadow his actual skills
in the ring.

02:02.164 --> 02:03.916
I doubt Cooper agrees
with that assessment tonight.

02:03.999 --> 02:05.376
Let’s just hope
Clay can put this bloke

02:05.459 --> 02:06.544
out of his misery soon.

02:06.627 --> 02:08.003
ANNOUNCER:
I think we may have all

02:08.087 --> 02:09.672
underestimated
Cassius Clay, Ronnie.

02:09.755 --> 02:12.091
Perhaps he is
as good as he says he is.

02:12.174 --> 02:13.175
(bell dinging)

02:13.259 --> 02:14.426
Finish him off!

02:14.510 --> 02:16.595
I’ll finish him
when I’m good and ready to.

02:16.679 --> 02:18.180
-(crowd cheering)
-Let’s go, Cooper.

02:18.264 --> 02:19.431
REFEREE:
Fight!

02:19.515 --> 02:21.058
You ain’t got nowhere to be,
do you, Henry?

02:21.141 --> 02:23.018
ANGELO:
Jab him! Jab him!

02:23.102 --> 02:24.770
-Push!
-Let’s go.

02:24.854 --> 02:27.648
-(grunting)
-(crowd shouting)

02:27.731 --> 02:31.151
ANGELO: Let’s go, now, Cassius.
Let’s go.

02:31.235 --> 02:32.361
There you are.

02:32.444 --> 02:34.154
(crowd booing)

02:34.238 --> 02:35.656
ANGELO:
There you are.

02:35.739 --> 02:37.157
-ANGELO: That’s right.
-No holding, Henry.

02:37.241 --> 02:39.368
-Cooper, hang on.
-Don’t stay in too long. Move.

02:39.451 --> 02:41.245
-Move!
-Dance, Cassius. Keep moving.

02:41.328 --> 02:43.497
-Come on. -ANNOUNCER 2:
Clay is mocking Cooper.

02:43.581 --> 02:45.541
ANGELO:
There it is. There you are.

02:45.624 --> 02:46.834
Got to dance with him.
You got to dance.

02:46.917 --> 02:47.918
ANNOUNCER 2:
The crowd doesn’t like it.

02:48.002 --> 02:49.879
None of that.

02:49.962 --> 02:51.297
-Hands! Hands up!
-Come on, Henry!

02:51.380 --> 02:53.966
-What is he doing?
-I don’t know. Playing around.

02:54.049 --> 02:55.050
ANGELO:
Don’t walk this guy down.

02:55.134 --> 02:56.302
BUNDINI:
That’s how you do it.

02:56.385 --> 02:58.220
ANGELO:
Keep your eyes in the ring.

02:58.304 --> 02:59.305
Is that Elizabeth Taylor?

02:59.388 --> 03:00.848
ANNOUNCER:
Anything might happen.

03:00.931 --> 03:02.516
Keep those hands up!

03:02.600 --> 03:03.809
There you go!

03:03.893 --> 03:05.144
-Oh!
-(crowd clamoring)

03:05.227 --> 03:06.228
ANNOUNCER: That was
the end of the fourth round,

03:06.312 --> 03:07.563
and he hit him.

03:07.646 --> 03:08.647
-Get up! -So close,
before the end of the round.

03:08.731 --> 03:10.065
ANGELO:
That was lucky.

03:10.149 --> 03:11.525
Get up there, Cassius. Come on.

03:11.609 --> 03:12.902
Get up.

03:12.985 --> 03:14.778
You’re okay!
You’re okay! Come on.

03:14.862 --> 03:17.364
ANNOUNCER:
Clay took one chance too many,

03:17.448 --> 03:19.700
and he still doesn’t know
where he is.

03:19.783 --> 03:22.077
He’s still half out, Clay.

03:22.161 --> 03:23.954
MYRON:
I want you to imagine a man

03:24.038 --> 03:25.956
who, for 25 years of his life,

03:26.040 --> 03:29.043
arrived to work
every morning at 9:00.

03:29.126 --> 03:31.003
You could set your watch
by him.

03:31.086 --> 03:33.213
Then suddenly one morning,
after 25 years

03:33.297 --> 03:35.633
of punctual 9:00-in-the-morning
appearances,

03:35.716 --> 03:38.218
not only is he late but
he doesn’t look like himself.

03:38.302 --> 03:41.639
Big lump on his head,
two black eyes, bloody nose,

03:41.722 --> 03:44.725
torn lip, clothes ripped
and disheveled.

03:44.808 --> 03:47.561
His boss says, "What in
the world happened to you?"

03:47.645 --> 03:50.689
He says, "Oh, fell down
a whole flight of stairs,

03:50.773 --> 03:52.608
almost got killed."

03:52.691 --> 03:55.277
His boss says,
"So this took you an hour?"

03:55.361 --> 03:56.695
(laughter)

03:56.779 --> 03:58.781
(applause)

03:58.864 --> 04:00.950
JESS:
Jules, work with us.

04:01.033 --> 04:02.785
JULES:
The Copa has rules.

04:02.868 --> 04:04.995
Band members sit
in the bandstand.

04:05.079 --> 04:06.330
Cliff’s not dressed.

04:06.413 --> 04:08.165
You don’t even have
a chair for him.

04:08.248 --> 04:10.751
-If your guy’s a real singer...
-Real singer?

04:10.834 --> 04:13.170
...then he don’t need no guitar
player on the floor with him.

04:13.253 --> 04:15.214
My guy’s first single
was number one in America.

04:15.297 --> 04:16.882
He ain’t had any hits in here.

04:16.966 --> 04:18.300
I never should’ve booked him.

04:18.384 --> 04:20.469
We could’ve had Mark Wilson
in this slot.

04:20.552 --> 04:22.513
Who? The magician?

04:22.596 --> 04:24.431
From The Magical Land
of Allakazam?

04:24.515 --> 04:26.058
(chuckles)
I love that show, man.

04:26.141 --> 04:29.353
See? Even that guy knows,
and he looks like an idiot.

04:29.436 --> 04:31.438
-Fuck you, man.
-MYRON: My dear good friends,

04:31.522 --> 04:32.898
you’ve been
a wonderful audience.

04:32.982 --> 04:34.525
Thank you very much,
and good night.

04:34.608 --> 04:35.943
-JULES: So?
-Thank you.

04:36.026 --> 04:38.153
Should I tell Myron
to do an encore?

04:38.237 --> 04:40.781
He’s the one
these people paid to see.

04:40.864 --> 04:42.700
JESS:
Shh.

04:42.783 --> 04:44.535
-Sam. -MAN: Give it up
for Myron Cohen,

04:44.618 --> 04:45.828
-ladies and gentlemen.
-(applause)

04:45.911 --> 04:46.954
Myron Cohen.

04:47.037 --> 04:49.456
-All right, fine. Fine.
-Fine.

04:51.917 --> 04:54.878
-MAN: Next up... -Better not
fuck up my arrangements.

04:54.962 --> 04:56.922
...we have a young man
coming to the Copacabana

04:57.006 --> 04:58.298
for the very first time.

04:58.382 --> 05:02.052
You all know him from
his hit song "You Send Me."

05:02.136 --> 05:06.598
Ladies and gents, let’s give
a warm Copacabana welcome

05:06.682 --> 05:08.892
-for Sam Cooke!
-(applause)

05:08.976 --> 05:11.061
(band playing
lively jazz music)

05:19.111 --> 05:20.779
It’s great to be
at the Copacabana!

05:20.863 --> 05:21.905
(music ends)

05:21.989 --> 05:23.866
How’s everybody
feeling tonight?

05:23.949 --> 05:25.909
(people clearing throats)

05:25.993 --> 05:28.829
(scattered applause)

05:28.912 --> 05:31.832
Uh, I-I want
to tell you that, uh,

05:31.915 --> 05:34.126
ever since I started singing,

05:34.209 --> 05:36.879
before I even knew
I wanted to be a singer,

05:36.962 --> 05:39.048
playing the Copa has always
been a dream of mine.

05:39.131 --> 05:40.340
So thank you for being here

05:40.424 --> 05:43.427
on the night
that dream comes true.

05:43.510 --> 05:45.679
(people coughing)

05:48.891 --> 05:52.311
I thought I’d start off
this evening, uh,

05:52.394 --> 05:56.440
with something that
you all might recognize.

05:56.523 --> 05:57.816
Boys.

06:01.278 --> 06:03.697
-(band playing "Tammy")
-Cigarettes, ma’am?

06:03.781 --> 06:05.991
No.

06:12.873 --> 06:15.167
(quiet whispering)

06:15.250 --> 06:20.380
♪ I hear the cottonwood ♪

06:20.464 --> 06:22.841
♪ Whispering ♪

06:22.925 --> 06:25.094
-♪ Above ♪
-(microphone stand clanks)

06:25.177 --> 06:26.470
(sighs)

06:26.553 --> 06:28.639
-♪ Tammy ♪
-(trumpet playing off-key)

06:28.722 --> 06:31.642
♪ Tammy ♪

06:31.725 --> 06:33.769
♪ Tammy’s my love ♪

06:33.852 --> 06:36.605
-What time is it?
What time is it? -Uh...

06:36.688 --> 06:40.150
♪ The old hooty owl ♪

06:41.110 --> 06:43.445
♪ Hooty-hoos to... ♪

06:43.529 --> 06:45.114
I liked this song
so much better

06:45.197 --> 06:47.241
when Debbie Reynolds sang it.

06:47.324 --> 06:49.618
-♪ Tammy ♪
-Come on, let’s go.

06:49.701 --> 06:51.787
♪ Tammy ♪

06:51.870 --> 06:56.250
♪ Tammy’s my love... ♪

06:57.960 --> 07:00.254
-(door opens)
-(distant applause)

07:02.548 --> 07:04.716
(sighs)

07:05.551 --> 07:06.844
(Jess sighs)

07:06.927 --> 07:09.805
Boy, you... you really did
bomb tonight, Sam.

07:09.888 --> 07:11.140
Motherfucker,
have you ever made

07:11.223 --> 07:12.516
a quarter of a million dollars
singing?

07:12.599 --> 07:14.393
-Sam, no.
-Well, I have.

07:14.476 --> 07:17.104
So until you do,
keep your fucking mouth shut!

07:17.187 --> 07:19.064
(woman gasps)

07:21.066 --> 07:22.442
(door closes)

07:24.987 --> 07:27.156
(man chuckling)

07:29.449 --> 07:31.702
-He ain’t wrong, though.
-(laughing)

07:31.785 --> 07:34.204
You did kind of stink
the place up tonight.

07:34.288 --> 07:35.664
(chuckles):
Yeah, I did.

07:35.747 --> 07:37.207
Told him not to sing that song.

07:37.291 --> 07:40.210
-He got all them hits;
he chose that one. -I know.

07:40.294 --> 07:42.421
(upbeat blues song playing)

07:44.256 --> 07:48.051
♪ Whew!
It’s hot as shit out here ♪

07:48.927 --> 07:50.470
♪ Where’s my drink? ♪

07:50.554 --> 07:52.389
♪ Mm ♪

07:52.472 --> 07:55.559
♪ With the dirt-brown ground,
leaving from L.A. ♪

07:55.642 --> 07:59.146
♪ Heading down to the South
where the gators like to play ♪

07:59.229 --> 08:01.940
♪ Engine roaring nice
from that old red clay ♪

08:02.024 --> 08:06.320
♪ On my soapbox spittin’,
listen what I gotta say ♪

08:06.403 --> 08:08.447
♪ Howl for me, daddy ♪

08:08.530 --> 08:11.158
♪ Sure sound sweet ♪

08:12.993 --> 08:15.370
♪ Say something, baby ♪

08:15.454 --> 08:17.789
♪ Say something deep ♪

08:19.708 --> 08:21.543
♪ What you say, daddy? ♪

08:21.627 --> 08:23.545
♪ Say something deep... ♪

08:23.629 --> 08:25.547
(insects trilling,
birds chirping)

08:25.631 --> 08:28.634
(song continues faintly
over car stereo)

08:29.635 --> 08:32.137
(brakes squeak)

08:32.221 --> 08:34.514
-(music stops)
-(engine turns off)

08:46.902 --> 08:49.071
(bell jingles)

08:55.369 --> 08:57.329
Yes? May I help you?

08:57.412 --> 08:58.455
Yes, ma’am.

08:58.538 --> 08:59.706
I’m here to see Mr. Carlton.

08:59.790 --> 09:01.458
Would you tell him
that Jim Brown is...

09:01.541 --> 09:03.627
Jim Brown? Oh.

09:03.710 --> 09:05.379
God! From the NFL!

09:05.462 --> 09:06.505
(both chuckle)

09:06.588 --> 09:08.173
Grandpa!

09:08.257 --> 09:12.678
Jim Brown from the NFL is here,
and he wants to see you.

09:12.761 --> 09:15.472
(laughing):
Well, I never.

09:15.555 --> 09:17.557
(chuckles)

09:17.641 --> 09:20.060
Never.

09:20.143 --> 09:23.355
Would you look
at who’s on my porch.

09:23.438 --> 09:26.066
(chuckles):
James Nathaniel Brown.

09:26.149 --> 09:27.776
Hello there, Mr. Carlton.

09:27.859 --> 09:28.902
Don’t you "hello" me.

09:28.986 --> 09:30.737
Put her there, son.

09:30.821 --> 09:31.863
(chuckles)

09:31.947 --> 09:34.324
Come now, have a seat with me.

09:34.408 --> 09:36.410
Can I get you
something to drink?

09:36.493 --> 09:37.703
Lemonade, maybe?

09:37.786 --> 09:39.329
Oh, that’s all right.
Thank you, though.

09:39.413 --> 09:41.164
Well, suit yourself.

09:41.248 --> 09:43.750
I’m certainly having me some.

09:43.834 --> 09:45.711
Fetch us a couple glasses
of that lemonade,

09:45.794 --> 09:47.462
-would you, sweetie?
-(in distance): Yes, Grandpa.

09:47.546 --> 09:49.172
Just in case
you change your mind.

09:49.256 --> 09:50.340
-Hmm.
-(chuckles)

09:50.424 --> 09:52.384
How long you been
back on the island?

09:52.467 --> 09:54.303
Oh, I just got in last night.

09:54.386 --> 09:57.097
And you came by to say hello?

09:57.180 --> 09:58.932
How thoughtful of you, Jimmy.

09:59.016 --> 10:01.560
Well, my aunt says
you were anxious to see me.

10:01.643 --> 10:04.229
I’m an early riser, so I
thought I’d come right on over.

10:04.313 --> 10:06.064
Mm, the early bird
does catch the worm.

10:06.148 --> 10:08.400
-Mm.
-But you already know that.

10:08.483 --> 10:10.777
You caught a hell of
a lot of worms this year.

10:10.861 --> 10:11.945
(both chuckle)

10:12.029 --> 10:13.780
I guess you can say that.

10:13.864 --> 10:18.869
No man who’s run
1,860 yards in a season

10:18.952 --> 10:20.829
needs to be so humble.

10:20.912 --> 10:24.624
Actually, it was 1,863.

10:24.708 --> 10:26.460
-Oh, that’s more like it.
-Mm-hmm.

10:26.543 --> 10:29.421
That record is gonna stand
the test of time.

10:29.504 --> 10:31.298
You know, I’d happily
give that record back

10:31.381 --> 10:33.467
for a win over the Packers
in that last game.

10:33.550 --> 10:36.219
(chuckles) That Packers win
is gonna be forgotten

10:36.303 --> 10:39.056
by anyone who doesn’t live
in Goose Bay by tomorrow.

10:39.139 --> 10:40.390
Hmm.

10:40.474 --> 10:43.352
Your record is gonna be
remembered forever.

10:43.435 --> 10:45.103
I don’t see why
I can’t have the record

10:45.187 --> 10:46.813
and the win next time.

10:46.897 --> 10:49.107
Right you are, son.
Right you are.

10:50.359 --> 10:54.780
Jimmy, I-I just wanted
to-to let you know,

10:54.863 --> 10:57.407
if there’s ever anything
I can do for you,

10:57.491 --> 11:00.327
you should never hesitate
to reach out.

11:02.662 --> 11:05.040
Um, that’s...

11:06.291 --> 11:08.085
That’s-that’s mighty kind
of you, sir.

11:08.168 --> 11:10.670
Oh, our families go way back.

11:10.754 --> 11:12.005
Been looking after one another

11:12.089 --> 11:14.633
since the first folks
settled on this island.

11:14.716 --> 11:18.678
I wanted to make sure
that I told you face-to-face,

11:18.762 --> 11:23.350
as long as I’m still here,
that ain’t ever gonna change.

11:24.518 --> 11:26.311
Well, my aunt would be
very happy to hear

11:26.395 --> 11:29.564
such a kind sentiment
from you, Mr. Carlton.

11:29.648 --> 11:32.526
Not everyone else on the island
has been so supportive.

11:32.609 --> 11:34.361
Ah, crabs in a barrel, I say.

11:34.444 --> 11:36.405
-To hell with them all.
-(chuckles)

11:36.488 --> 11:40.075
I, for one, think
that you are a credit

11:40.158 --> 11:44.204
not only to this community but
to the entire state of Georgia.

11:44.287 --> 11:45.789
I’ve never been prouder to say

11:45.872 --> 11:47.791
that I live on
St. Simons Island

11:47.874 --> 11:49.918
-than I am now.
-Mm.

11:50.001 --> 11:53.755
And I would make
a point of adding

11:53.839 --> 11:56.716
"the place where
the great Jim Brown is from."

11:56.800 --> 11:58.760
(chuckles)

11:58.844 --> 11:59.928
Huh?

12:01.805 --> 12:04.307
-Here you boys go.
-Ah.

12:04.391 --> 12:05.642
Two lemonades.

12:05.725 --> 12:07.102
Thank you, darling.

12:07.185 --> 12:10.147
-Well, thank you.
-Mm.

12:10.230 --> 12:12.691
Uh, sorry to bother you while
you’re entertaining, Grandpa,

12:12.774 --> 12:15.193
but if you could
come move that bureau,

12:15.277 --> 12:16.695
when-when you have a moment.

12:16.778 --> 12:18.864
Oh. Sorry.

12:18.947 --> 12:20.365
I almost forgot.
(chuckles)

12:20.449 --> 12:23.910
You, uh... you moving
some furniture?

12:23.994 --> 12:25.412
Mm-hmm.

12:25.495 --> 12:29.416
Well, you know, uh, you should
let me help you with that.

12:29.499 --> 12:31.084
Ah, so considerate
of you, Jimmy,

12:31.168 --> 12:33.587
but you know we don’t allow
niggers in the house,

12:33.670 --> 12:35.964
so it’s quite all right.

12:36.047 --> 12:39.843
It really is wonderful
to see you, son.

12:39.926 --> 12:42.012
You keep up the good work.

12:43.263 --> 12:45.223
Do us all proud.

12:48.101 --> 12:49.269
MIKE WALLACE:
While city officials,

12:49.352 --> 12:51.897
state agencies, white liberals

12:51.980 --> 12:55.775
and sober-minded Negroes
stand idly by,

12:55.859 --> 12:57.235
a group of Negro dissenters is

12:57.319 --> 12:59.654
taking to street corner
step ladders, church pulpits,

12:59.738 --> 13:01.448
sports arenas
and ballroom platforms

13:01.531 --> 13:05.744
across the United States
to preach a gospel of hate

13:05.827 --> 13:07.954
that would set off
a federal investigation

13:08.038 --> 13:10.332
if it were preached
by Southern whites.

13:10.415 --> 13:12.459
For some time between
now and 1970,

13:12.542 --> 13:15.086
Elijah Muhammad,
founder and spiritual leader

13:15.170 --> 13:16.296
-of the group,
-(chuckles softly)

13:16.379 --> 13:17.964
has intimated
that he will give the call

13:18.048 --> 13:20.133
for the destruction
of the white man.

13:20.217 --> 13:21.843
Here you will hear
Elijah Muhammad

13:21.927 --> 13:23.720
introduced by
minister Malcolm X,

13:23.803 --> 13:25.263
the Muslims’ New York leader

13:25.347 --> 13:27.224
and ambassador-at-large
for the movement.

13:27.307 --> 13:30.477
Now, in the church,
we-we used to sing the song

13:30.560 --> 13:32.562
"Good News,
the Chariot Is Coming."

13:32.646 --> 13:34.981
-Is-is that right or wrong?
-CROWD: That’s right.

13:35.065 --> 13:39.653
But what we must bear in mind
is that what’s good news to you

13:39.736 --> 13:42.030
might be bad news to another.

13:42.113 --> 13:44.491
And while you sit here today

13:44.574 --> 13:47.744
knowing that you have come
to hear good news,

13:47.827 --> 13:50.413
you must realize in advance,

13:50.497 --> 13:53.166
what’s good news for the sheep,

13:53.250 --> 13:55.585
well, that might be
bad news for the wolf.

13:55.669 --> 13:57.379
(crowd murmuring, applauding)

13:57.462 --> 13:59.214
(door opens)

14:01.216 --> 14:03.218
I expected you back hours ago.

14:03.301 --> 14:06.012
I know, I know, I know, I know.

14:06.096 --> 14:08.932
I got back as fast as I could.

14:09.015 --> 14:11.768
-Thank goodness you’re safe.
-(sighs)

14:11.851 --> 14:13.603
...and the wisest
and most fearless

14:13.687 --> 14:15.480
Black man in America...

14:15.564 --> 14:17.065
Where are the girls?

14:17.148 --> 14:18.608
I put them to bed.

14:18.692 --> 14:22.404
Oh, I promised I’d be here
in time to tuck them in.

14:26.157 --> 14:27.492
(clicks tongue)

14:28.368 --> 14:29.828
I’m really sorry.

14:29.911 --> 14:32.372
But you can put them to bed
tomorrow night.

14:32.455 --> 14:34.082
-Right.
-(chuckles softly)

14:34.165 --> 14:36.042
Tomorrow.

14:38.545 --> 14:40.714
Did you speak to him?

14:42.299 --> 14:43.633
(smacks lips)

14:43.717 --> 14:45.385
Yes.

14:46.303 --> 14:47.762
And?

14:49.389 --> 14:53.518
Louis X said that if I decide
to leave the Nation of Islam,

14:53.602 --> 14:55.395
I will be doing so on my own.

14:55.478 --> 14:57.772
-Damn him!
-Betty.

14:58.648 --> 15:00.275
Please.

15:00.358 --> 15:03.820
Please just...
don’t wake up the girls.

15:03.903 --> 15:06.448
He wouldn’t even be
in the Nation if not for you,

15:06.531 --> 15:08.199
let alone running
the Boston temple.

15:08.283 --> 15:11.578
And he remains thankful
for my mentorship.

15:13.121 --> 15:16.291
You told him about
the Messenger’s indiscretions?

15:16.374 --> 15:19.836
All of the secretaries,
all of the children?

15:19.919 --> 15:21.671
And that didn’t
sway him at all?

15:21.755 --> 15:22.797
No, the Honorable
Elijah Muhammad...

15:22.881 --> 15:23.882
Oh, don’t say "Honorable."

15:23.965 --> 15:25.342
...was his lure to the Nation,

15:25.425 --> 15:29.095
just like he was for me
and so many others.

15:30.096 --> 15:31.723
Now imagine convincing someone

15:31.806 --> 15:34.851
to convert to Christianity and
then telling that same person

15:34.934 --> 15:36.144
to leave the church because

15:36.227 --> 15:37.979
Christ was not
who you said he was.

15:38.063 --> 15:40.231
Louis could stroll right over
to any of the seedy apartments

15:40.315 --> 15:43.360
Elijah Muhammad has those
poor young girls holed up in

15:43.443 --> 15:46.196
and see the proof of his deeds
with his own eyes.

15:46.279 --> 15:50.033
Perhaps Louis X just isn’t
ready to see that truth.

15:50.116 --> 15:52.327
Maybe none of them are.

16:01.711 --> 16:04.255
What are we gonna do now?

16:04.339 --> 16:06.091
The Nation owns this house.

16:06.174 --> 16:07.717
The car.

16:07.801 --> 16:09.511
Everything we have.

16:09.594 --> 16:11.596
The second they learn
about your plan...

16:11.680 --> 16:14.766
I am hoping our friendship
will keep Brother Louis

16:14.849 --> 16:17.018
from sharing our plans
with anyone else.

16:17.102 --> 16:18.311
You can’t count on that.

16:18.395 --> 16:20.355
I have to.

16:20.438 --> 16:24.317
I have to until I can
make other arrangements.

16:27.696 --> 16:30.407
What else can be done?

16:30.490 --> 16:35.954
You-- We are all alone
if we go through with this.

16:38.331 --> 16:40.208
For the moment.

16:40.291 --> 16:44.879
But I have one more
potential ace up my sleeve.

16:46.381 --> 16:47.882
What?

16:47.966 --> 16:50.051
♪ ♪

16:56.474 --> 16:57.809
(splash)

17:10.029 --> 17:12.323
He can’t even swim.

17:12.407 --> 17:14.951
That boy gonna mess around
and drown.

17:16.494 --> 17:19.205
You need to get on out of there
’fore you get yourself killed.

17:19.289 --> 17:21.458
He’s right, kid. You need to
get your head into this fight.

17:21.541 --> 17:23.918
My head is
into the fight, Angie.

17:24.002 --> 17:25.754
You sat in on any more
of Liston’s training sessions

17:25.837 --> 17:27.338
-like I asked?
-(grunts)

17:27.422 --> 17:28.506
No need.

17:28.590 --> 17:30.133
No need, no need.

17:30.216 --> 17:33.136
Watching Sonny Liston train
is like... being at the circus.

17:33.219 --> 17:35.513
He looks like one of them
big ugly bears they have

17:35.597 --> 17:37.098
riding around
on tiny little bikes.

17:37.182 --> 17:38.975
All he needs is that
itty-bitty hat on his head.

17:39.058 --> 17:40.727
He ain’t no boxer.
He’s an animal.

17:40.810 --> 17:43.980
He’s an animal that can tear
you apart if you don’t focus.

17:44.063 --> 17:45.106
-Mm-hmm.
-You make the same mistakes

17:45.190 --> 17:46.566
with him
as you did with Cooper,

17:46.649 --> 17:48.026
you won’t be walking away
from it.

17:48.109 --> 17:49.778
I won that Cooper fight,
didn’t I?

17:49.861 --> 17:50.862
You got saved by the bell.

17:50.945 --> 17:52.447
And he would’ve finished
the job

17:52.530 --> 17:53.823
if they didn’t stop the fight
from all the bleeding.

17:53.907 --> 17:55.325
Oh, woulda, coulda,
shoulda, didn’t.

17:55.408 --> 17:57.160
A win is a win, Ferdie.

17:57.243 --> 17:58.620
I’ll be back in a bit.

17:58.703 --> 18:00.205
And where on earth
are you going?

18:00.288 --> 18:01.414
To check on Malcolm.

18:01.498 --> 18:02.749
Oh, good grief.

18:06.002 --> 18:08.171
You got something else
on your mind, Angie?

18:08.254 --> 18:10.965
Do I need to remind you how
unhappy the Louisville Group is

18:11.049 --> 18:12.300
about him being here?

18:12.383 --> 18:13.593
What they got to be mad about?

18:13.676 --> 18:15.595
I been training hard as hell
for this fight.

18:15.678 --> 18:17.096
Well, they’re the ones paying
for all the training.

18:17.180 --> 18:18.389
They’re paying for all of us.

18:18.473 --> 18:19.724
I’m just letting you know

18:19.808 --> 18:21.559
they’ve been giving me
a lot of grief.

18:21.643 --> 18:23.102
What business is Malcolm
of theirs?

18:23.186 --> 18:24.938
You don’t understand why
a bunch of white businessmen

18:25.021 --> 18:26.689
might be a little stung
by a guy

18:26.773 --> 18:29.442
who says they’re all
natural born demons?

18:29.526 --> 18:32.278
Mm-hmm. That’d do it.

18:32.362 --> 18:34.197
He said "devils."

18:34.280 --> 18:36.407
Malcolm’s never been anything
but kind to you, Angelo.

18:36.491 --> 18:38.493
I know,
but the investors only know

18:38.576 --> 18:40.954
what they see on TV,
and that ain’t good.

18:41.037 --> 18:42.163
They pay for my training.

18:42.247 --> 18:43.915
They don’t get to choose
my friends for me.

18:43.998 --> 18:46.000
Well, training’s what they want
their money going towards,

18:46.084 --> 18:49.420
not some white-man-hating
demagogue’s airfare.

18:49.504 --> 18:51.506
What did the investors say
when they gave me my money?

18:52.841 --> 18:54.384
That it was yours to do with...

18:54.467 --> 18:57.554
To do with as I please, Angie.

18:57.637 --> 18:59.180
And if it pleases me
to bring my friend down

18:59.264 --> 19:00.849
to give me
the spiritual support I need

19:00.932 --> 19:01.933
to win this fight,

19:02.016 --> 19:03.184
then that’s what I’m gonna do.

19:03.268 --> 19:04.519
They want their money back,

19:04.602 --> 19:06.771
I’ll pay it back to all of ’em,
with interest,

19:06.855 --> 19:08.648
after the fight.
Now, if you all will excuse me,

19:08.731 --> 19:10.567
I’ll see you back here
in an hour.

19:10.650 --> 19:12.235
SAM:
♪ Don’t make it rougher ♪

19:12.318 --> 19:16.364
♪ And don’t make me suffer,
just... ♪

19:16.447 --> 19:18.700
SAM and BARBARA:
♪ Put me down easy. ♪

19:18.783 --> 19:19.868
BUNDINI:
He’ll be all right.

19:19.951 --> 19:21.077
You got to have faith in him.

19:21.160 --> 19:22.704
Got to have
a little bit of faith.

19:22.787 --> 19:23.913
BARBARA:
That sounds nice.

19:23.997 --> 19:25.373
SAM:
It does, doesn’t it?

19:25.456 --> 19:28.251
♪ If you found somebody new ♪

19:28.334 --> 19:31.421
♪ There’s nothing I can do ♪

19:31.504 --> 19:35.258
-♪ But ask you to ♪
-(chuckles softly)

19:35.341 --> 19:39.345
♪ Go easy on me, baby doll ♪

19:39.429 --> 19:43.182
♪ Do me this service,
break my fall. ♪

19:43.266 --> 19:45.018
Ah, shit.

19:45.101 --> 19:46.102
What?

19:46.185 --> 19:47.645
That sounds great.

19:47.729 --> 19:51.149
If I was singing it, maybe,
but not for L.C.

19:51.232 --> 19:53.318
It don’t sound
like nothing he’d ever say.

19:53.401 --> 19:55.987
(chuckles)
You got that right.

19:56.070 --> 19:57.697
He’s more like...

19:57.780 --> 20:00.700
♪ Get on over here, girl, and
let me smell them panties. ♪

20:00.783 --> 20:02.410
-’Ey!
-(laughs)

20:02.493 --> 20:04.287
-(laughs)
-Your brother is so country.

20:04.370 --> 20:05.997
Yeah, look who’s talking.

20:06.080 --> 20:07.248
I’m sophisticated.

20:07.332 --> 20:08.791
I don’t know why
I go through all the trouble

20:08.875 --> 20:10.919
of getting
a nice hotel room like this

20:11.002 --> 20:12.921
for a old country gal like you.

20:13.004 --> 20:14.923
I didn’t ask to stay
at the Fontainebleau.

20:15.006 --> 20:16.341
I’d have been perfectly happy

20:16.424 --> 20:17.926
over at the Sir John
with Cassius

20:18.009 --> 20:19.344
or the Hampton House
with Malcolm

20:19.427 --> 20:22.013
and the rest
of the Black folks like us.

20:27.560 --> 20:29.938
But I do like it here.

20:31.272 --> 20:33.316
It’s nice.

20:38.905 --> 20:41.491
And, uh...

20:42.909 --> 20:46.663
...I am glad I decided to come
down here for this, Sam.

20:47.538 --> 20:48.873
With you.

20:53.002 --> 20:57.465
You haven’t sung to me
in... a long time.

21:00.134 --> 21:01.344
(clicks tongue)

21:01.427 --> 21:03.471
I know it.
(exhales)

21:05.139 --> 21:07.016
(strums guitar)

21:07.100 --> 21:08.476
(phone rings)

21:10.979 --> 21:12.105
(phone clicks in cradle)

21:12.188 --> 21:13.189
Hello.

21:13.272 --> 21:14.315
MALCOLM:
Brother Sam?

21:14.399 --> 21:16.401
Uh, Malcolm!

21:16.484 --> 21:17.777
(Malcolm chuckles softly)

21:17.860 --> 21:19.737
MALCOLM: Is Brother Cassius
there with you?

21:19.821 --> 21:23.366
No. He’s probably doing some
last-minute prep for the fight.

21:23.449 --> 21:25.201
-Why?
-Oh, uh...

21:25.284 --> 21:27.203
I thought he might come by

21:27.286 --> 21:29.706
before heading
to the convention center

21:29.789 --> 21:32.208
so we might have a word or two.

21:32.291 --> 21:33.876
Well, have you tried Jim?

21:33.960 --> 21:36.462
MALCOLM: Yes. Uh,
Jimmy hadn’t seen him, either.

21:36.546 --> 21:39.674
Well, if he calls, I’ll tell
him you’re looking for him.

21:39.757 --> 21:41.592
MALCOLM: Ah. I appreciate that,
Brother Sam.

21:41.676 --> 21:43.928
SAM: We’ll see you
at the convention center.

21:44.012 --> 21:45.805
-Yeah. I wouldn’t miss it.
-All right.

21:52.228 --> 21:54.647
(sighs)

21:54.731 --> 21:55.732
(knocking)

21:55.815 --> 21:56.858
Come in.

21:56.941 --> 21:58.735
(music playing in distance)

21:58.818 --> 22:00.278
Yes, Brother Kareem.

22:00.361 --> 22:02.655
You have a visitor,
Brother Malcolm.

22:06.993 --> 22:09.454
(Malcolm chuckles)

22:09.537 --> 22:11.706
(laughing)

22:11.789 --> 22:13.624
Brother Cassius.

22:13.708 --> 22:15.293
I thought you might not
be able to make it.

22:15.376 --> 22:17.378
Hey, man, ain’t no way
I’m going into that ring

22:17.462 --> 22:18.880
without my insurance policy.

22:18.963 --> 22:20.882
-All right.
-(exhales)

22:27.305 --> 22:29.390
♪ ♪

22:42.403 --> 22:44.697
Allahu Akbar.

22:47.408 --> 22:50.036
(exhales)

22:52.246 --> 22:54.040
MALCOLM (whispers):
Cassius.

22:54.123 --> 22:55.416
(Cassius clears throat)

22:55.500 --> 22:57.418
-CASSIUS: Thank you.
-Mm-hmm.

22:58.628 --> 23:00.838
(praying in Arabic)

23:10.431 --> 23:12.809
Allahu Akbar.

23:23.027 --> 23:25.238
(praying in Arabic)

23:39.877 --> 23:43.131
(praying in Arabic)

23:59.856 --> 24:01.983
MALCOLM:
Allahu Akbar.

24:15.371 --> 24:18.207
(breathing heavily)

24:30.178 --> 24:33.347
-You ready for tonight?
-(sniffs)

24:33.431 --> 24:34.765
Man, I’ve been training
three years for this fight.

24:34.849 --> 24:36.684
(chuckles): I’m as ready
as a person can be.

24:36.767 --> 24:38.227
Well, uh...

24:38.311 --> 24:41.314
Well, still, it might not hurt
to just tone down the rhetoric

24:41.397 --> 24:43.316
till after the fight.

24:44.108 --> 24:46.235
Why would I do that?

24:46.319 --> 24:47.904
May be easier for you
to focus, Cash,

24:47.987 --> 24:49.113
you know, if, for once,

24:49.197 --> 24:51.532
the only person
gunning for your head

24:51.616 --> 24:54.994
is the guy in the ring
and not the entire arena.

24:55.077 --> 24:57.246
You watch rassling?

24:57.330 --> 25:00.499
Wrestling, no, I can’t say
it’s part of my daily viewing.

25:00.583 --> 25:01.876
I figured not.

25:01.959 --> 25:04.295
Well, my favorite rassler
is Gorgeous George.

25:04.378 --> 25:06.005
A good-looking fellow,
I take it.

25:06.088 --> 25:08.549
In the European way, sure.

25:08.633 --> 25:11.344
Head full of blond hair
teased up into a nice do.

25:11.427 --> 25:13.930
-Ooh, the crowds must love him.
-Nah.

25:14.013 --> 25:17.642
He preens and he prances around
like a peacock,

25:17.725 --> 25:19.227
talking all kind of smack.

25:19.310 --> 25:20.895
They boo him,
they scream at him,

25:20.978 --> 25:24.106
and the more they scream,
the more he eggs ’em all on.

25:24.190 --> 25:26.108
Oh, so, so he-he’s the villain?

25:26.192 --> 25:28.069
Well, sort of.

25:28.152 --> 25:29.946
Rassling is complicated.

25:30.029 --> 25:31.155
And why would you model
yourself

25:31.239 --> 25:33.115
after a person
everyone hates, Cash?

25:33.199 --> 25:37.620
Because everyone in that arena
pays $100

25:37.703 --> 25:39.914
to see George lose.

25:39.997 --> 25:41.123
-(laughs)
-The way I figure it,

25:41.207 --> 25:42.416
win or lose the fight,

25:42.500 --> 25:43.751
George has already won the war.

25:43.834 --> 25:45.503
Well, maybe you fellas
just like

25:45.586 --> 25:47.380
going around with targets
on your backs.

25:47.463 --> 25:50.007
Oh, we learned from the best,
Brother Minister.

25:50.091 --> 25:51.509
Touché.

25:51.592 --> 25:52.760
(Malcolm chuckles)

25:52.843 --> 25:54.929
I got you a ticket
in the second row,

25:55.012 --> 25:56.055
right next to Sam.

25:56.138 --> 25:57.723
-And Jimmy?
-Oh, he’s doing, uh,

25:57.807 --> 25:59.976
commentary r-ringside,
but don’t worry.

26:00.059 --> 26:01.936
I already told all of them,
after the fight,

26:02.019 --> 26:05.564
we’re all coming back here
for the champ’s victory party.

26:06.565 --> 26:08.943
And did you...

26:09.026 --> 26:11.070
you tell ’em anything else?

26:12.989 --> 26:15.199
Oh. I didn’t.
I didn’t get around to it.

26:15.283 --> 26:17.285
I mean, um...
I mean, I plan to.

26:17.368 --> 26:18.911
No, no.
It’s all right, my brother.

26:18.995 --> 26:20.246
It’s, uh...
(inhales)

26:20.329 --> 26:22.873
The journey is different
for each of us.

26:23.874 --> 26:25.293
Thank you, Malcolm.

26:25.376 --> 26:28.170
-All right.
-(sighs)

26:28.254 --> 26:30.381
-I got to get back to my team.
-Mm-hmm.

26:30.464 --> 26:33.968
(grunts)
The fight... is at 10:00.

26:36.929 --> 26:38.431
-Don’t be late.
-I won’t.

26:38.514 --> 26:40.641
Peace be unto you,
young brother.

26:40.725 --> 26:42.810
-(door closes)
-Peace be unto you.

26:46.522 --> 26:47.523
ANGELO:
Stay on top of him.

26:47.606 --> 26:49.150
COMMENTATOR:
Clay in the white trunks

26:49.233 --> 26:51.402
with the red stripes,
and an inch and a half taller,

26:51.485 --> 26:54.155
is really bringing the fight
to the champ.

26:54.238 --> 26:55.823
Come on, sucka. Come on.

26:55.906 --> 26:57.992
Come on, Cassius!

26:58.075 --> 26:59.618
Honestly, I’m really happy
that we’re here.

26:59.702 --> 27:01.829
I think we got
a really good show. Oh.

27:01.912 --> 27:03.247
(chuckles):
Oh. All right.

27:03.331 --> 27:05.041
That’s what I’m talking about
right there.

27:05.124 --> 27:06.417
-Come on, Cash!
-Stay on him! Stay on him!

27:06.500 --> 27:07.668
Bang, bang, in and out,
Cassius.

27:07.752 --> 27:09.086
-Stay in there! Stay in there!
-Bang, bang.

27:09.170 --> 27:10.504
Outside, in and out, Cassius.

27:10.588 --> 27:11.964
There you are.
There you are.

27:12.048 --> 27:14.091
(cheering, shouting)

27:14.175 --> 27:15.676
ANGELO:
That’s what you want.

27:15.760 --> 27:17.261
Come on, boy.

27:17.345 --> 27:18.512
You gonna get that whuppin’.

27:18.596 --> 27:20.723
Give him
that Liston punch, baby!

27:20.806 --> 27:22.183
Yes. Yes.

27:22.266 --> 27:23.559
Now, see,
the thing about him, man,

27:23.642 --> 27:24.685
he stays on his toes.

27:24.769 --> 27:25.770
Nobody moves like him.

27:25.853 --> 27:27.813
He’s just dancing. He floats.

27:27.897 --> 27:29.315
All right, come on, Cash.
Come on, Cash.

27:30.441 --> 27:31.984
-Oh.
-Come on.

27:32.068 --> 27:33.736
That’s what you want.
That’s what you want.

27:33.819 --> 27:35.529
(gasping)

27:35.613 --> 27:37.531
-Stick him, Cash!
-JIM: Cash looks good.

27:37.615 --> 27:39.367
He’s staying warm.
He’s moving well. He’s--

27:39.450 --> 27:41.869
Oh, watch that hook, Cash.
Watch that hook.

27:41.952 --> 27:44.580
-WOMAN: Come on!
-(crowd shouting)

27:44.663 --> 27:46.874
Liston’s got Clay
against the ropes.

27:46.957 --> 27:48.751
Get off the ropes, Cash.
Get off the ropes.

